Summary: TESS is a transiting exoplanet-hunting mission. Yet its design is ideal to detect and observe eclipsing binary systems (EBs) as well: after all, exoplanets *are* binary systems with an extreme mass ratio. Thus, one of TESS mission legacies will certainly be the near-complete census of bright, short-period EBs in our galaxy. Given that EBs serve as fundamental calibrators of stellar masses, radii, temperatures and luminosities, and that better understanding stars has implications from exoplanets to galaxies, an EB census is one of the key projects for TESS. Completed studies already found nearly 5,000 EBs in short cadence data, and estimate 500,000+ EBs in full-frame images. Their continued discovery and analysis will yield the largest and the most accurate census of EBs to date.
